) VALUES (
    7, -- David Martinez
    '209429578973190336673242710141917128963',
    'Colorectal CA, Rectal Bleed',
    'Colorectal CA, Rectal Bleed',
    'What brings you in today? I\'ve been having this chronic abdominal pain that won\'t go away. It\'s been going on for months. I also feel bloated all the time, and my bowel movements are all over the place, alternating between diarrhea and constipation. That sounds quite uncomfortable. Have you noticed any other symptoms like weight loss or rectal bleeding? Yes, I\'ve lost about fifteen pounds without trying, and I\'ve seen blood in my stool a few times. That\'s concerning. Have you had any significant medical or surgical history in the past? No major surgeries, just the usual illnesses like colds and a couple of stomach bugs over the years. Nothing major, though. Alright. Let\'s proceed with a physical examination to get a better sense of what\'s going on. I\'ll palpate your abdomen to check for any tenderness or unusual masses. Does this hurt? Yes. A bit tender around here, the lower left side. I see. Given your symptoms and the tenderness you\'re experiencing, I recommend we perform a colonoscopy to get a clearer picture of what\'s happening inside your colon. Okay, if you think that\'s necessary. During the colonoscopy, we found multiple polyps and an ulcerative lesion in your sigmoid colon. We took biopsies of these areas. The results are back, and I\'m afraid it\'s not good news. The biopsy confirms that you have colorectal cancer. Oh no, that\'s terrifying. What happens next? We need to determine the extent of the cancer, so I\'ll arrange for you to have a staging CT scan. This will help us see if the cancer has spread to other parts of your body. All right. What are the treatment options? The main treatment will involve surgery to remove the affected part of your colon. Given the location of the ulcerative lesion in your sigmoid colon, we will need to perform a sigmoid colectomy. This means removing the section of the colon where the cancer is located, along with some surrounding tissue to ensure we get all of the cancerous cells. Is the surgery risky? All surgeries carry risks, but it\'s a standard procedure that we perform regularly. The primary risks include infection, bleeding, and complications related to anesthesia. However, the benefits of removing the cancerous section far outweigh these risks. You\'ll be under general anesthesia during the procedure, so you won\'t feel anything. What about after the surgery? What should I expect? Post surgery, you\'ll be in the hospital for several days. We\'ll monitor you closely for any complications and manage your pain. You\'ll start with a liquid diet and gradually move to solid foods as your bowel function returns. Recovery can take several weeks, and we\'ll give you detailed instructions on how to care for yourself at home. Will I need any additional treatments? Yes. After surgery, you\'ll be referred to an oncology unit to discuss chemotherapy. Chemotherapy can help kill any remaining cancer cells and reduce the risk of the cancer coming back. The oncology team will create a treatment plan tailored to your specific needs. What does chemotherapy involve? Chemotherapy involves using drugs to kill cancer cells. These drugs can be given orally or through an IV. The treatment is done in cycles, with periods of treatment followed by periods of rest. The oncology team will explain the specific regimen they recommend based on the staging of your cancer and other factors. Are there side effects to chemotherapy? Yes. Chemotherapy can cause side effects such as fatigue, hair loss, and increased susceptibility to infections, among others. The oncology team will work with you to manage these side effects and maintain your quality of life as much as possible. This is a lot to take in. How soon will all this happen? We\'ll schedule the CT scan as soon as possible, and based on those results, we can plan the surgery. It\'s important to move quickly, but we\'ll make sure you\'re fully informed and comfortable with each step before we proceed. I appreciate that. What can I do in the meantime? Try to maintain a balanced diet and stay as active as you can manage. It\'s also important to stay hydrated. We\'ll provide support and resources, including dietary advice and emotional support services, if you need them. Thank you. This is overwhelming, but I appreciate your clear explanations. You\'re welcome. I know this is a difficult time, but we\'re here to support you through every step of your treatment and recovery. We\'ll take this one step at a time and do everything we can to ensure the best possible outcome.',
    'Subjective:\nReports chronic abdominal pain persisting for months. Experiences constant bloating with alternating diarrhoea and constipation. Unintentional weight loss of 15 pounds. Episodes of rectal bleeding noted.\n\nPMHx: minor illnesses including colds and gastroenteritis. No major surgeries.\n\nObjective:\nAbdominal examination revealed tenderness in lower left quadrant on palpation.\n\nColonoscopy findings: multiple polyps and ulcerative lesion identified in sigmoid colon. Biopsies obtained from affected areas.\n\nAssessment & Plan:\n1. Colorectal Cancer:\nBiopsy results confirm colorectal cancer diagnosis based on tissue samples from sigmoid colon lesion.\n\nInvestigations: staging CT scan arranged to assess disease extent and potential metastases.\n\nTreatment planned: sigmoid colectomy to remove cancerous section of colon with surrounding tissue margins. Procedure involves general anaesthesia with standard surgical risks including infection, bleeding, and anaesthetic complications discussed.\n\nPost-operative care: hospital admission for several days with close monitoring. Progressive diet advancement from liquids to solids as bowel function returns. Recovery period of several weeks anticipated with detailed home care instructions to be provided.\n\nReferral to oncology unit for chemotherapy consultation. Chemotherapy regimen to be determined based on staging results and individualised treatment planning. Potential side effects including fatigue, alopecia, and increased infection susceptibility discussed.\n\nLifestyle modifications: maintain balanced diet and appropriate activity levels. Ensure adequate hydration. Dietary advice and emotional support services available.\n\nFollow-up:\nPrompt scheduling of staging CT scan. Surgical planning to proceed based on imaging results. Oncology referral for post-operative chemotherapy planning.',
    'GI Note 1 Updated',
    274,
    '2025-11-22 18:27:13'
);

-- Session 2: Lung Cancer (NSCLC)
