    7, -- David Martinez
    '48329781058232302558277795670340808022',
    'NSCLC, Cough, SOB',
    'NSCLC, Cough, SOB',
    'What brings you in today? I\'ve been having this cough that just won\'t go away. It\'s been a few months now, and it\'s getting worse. I\'ve also been feeling short of breath, especially when I\'m walking or doing anything physical. And I\'ve lost some weight without really trying. How much weight have you lost? About fifteen pounds over the last few months. Have you noticed any other symptoms, like fever, night sweats, or chest pain? Not really. It\'s mainly the cough and the shortness of breath. Any history of similar symptoms in the past? No, this is the first time I\'ve had anything like this. Can you tell me about your smoking history? I\'ve been smoking since I was about twenty, so it\'s been thirty five years now. I usually smoke about a pack a day. Have you had any significant past medical or surgical history? No major surgeries or hospitalizations. I had some high blood pressure, but it\'s been under control with medication. Do you take any other medications regularly? Just the blood pressure meds. How about family history? Any history of lung disease or cancer in your family? My dad had lung cancer. He passed away from it when I was a teenager. Given your symptoms and history, we performed a chest x-ray, which shows a suspicious mass in the right upper lobe of your lung. To get more information, I performed a bronchoscopy to take a closer look and obtain a biopsy of the mass. The biopsy results have confirmed that the mass is non small cell lung cancer. What does that mean exactly? Non small cell lung cancer, or NSCLC, is one of the main types of lung cancer. It\'s generally slower growing than small cell lung cancer, but it can still be quite serious. The next step is to determine the stage of the cancer, which will guide our treatment options. Staging involves a combination of imaging studies and sometimes additional biopsies to see if the cancer has spread to other parts of the body. What kind of imaging studies are we talking about? We usually start with a CT scan of the chest and abdomen, which can show us the size of the tumor and if it has spread to nearby lymph nodes or other organs. We might also do a PET scan, which can highlight areas of cancer activity throughout the body. Depending on what we find, we might need a brain MRI to check for any spread to the brain. That sounds like a lot. Is all this necessary? Yes, it\'s important to know the exact stage of the cancer to choose the best treatment plan. Once we have all the information, we can discuss the most appropriate options for you. What are the treatment options? Treatment depends on the stage and the overall health of the patient. For early stage NSCLC, surgery to remove the tumor is often the best option. This could involve a lobectomy, where we remove a lobe of the lung, or a pneumonectomy, where we remove an entire lung, depending on the size and location of the tumor. What if surgery isn\'t an option? If surgery isn\'t possible, either due to the stage of the cancer or other health issues, we consider radiation therapy and chemotherapy. Radiation can target the tumor directly, while chemotherapy uses drugs to kill cancer cells throughout the body. Sometimes, these treatments are used in combination. Are there side effects to these treatments? Yes, there are potential side effects. Surgery carries risks like any major operation, including infection and complications from anesthesia. Radiation can cause fatigue, skin changes, and damage to nearby organs. Chemotherapy can cause a range of side effects, including nausea, hair loss, and an increased risk of infection. We work to manage these side effects as much as possible. Is there anything else we can do? In some cases, targeted therapies or immunotherapies are options. These treatments focus on specific aspects of cancer cells or boost the body\'s immune system to fight the cancer. They\'re not suitable for everyone, but they can be very effective for some patients. What\'s the prognosis? Prognosis varies widely based on the stage at diagnosis,',
    'Main Respiratory Diagnosis:\n● Non-small cell lung cancer\n\nManagement Plan:\n● Staging investigations including CT chest and abdomen, PET scan, possible brain MRI\n● Treatment options to be discussed following staging results including surgery (lobectomy or pneumonectomy), radiation therapy, chemotherapy, targeted therapies or immunotherapy\n\nPresents with persistent cough for several months with progressive worsening. Reports associated dyspnoea on exertion and unintentional weight loss of 15 pounds over recent months. Denies fever, night sweats or chest pain.\n\nSignificant smoking history of 35 years at one pack daily since age 20. Past medical history includes hypertension controlled with medication. Family history notable for paternal lung cancer. No previous similar symptoms or major surgical history.\n\nChest X-ray demonstrated suspicious mass in right upper lobe. Bronchoscopy performed with biopsy of mass. Histopathology confirmed non-small cell lung cancer.\n\nStaging investigations recommended including CT chest and abdomen to assess tumour size and lymph node involvement. PET scan may be required to evaluate cancer activity throughout body. Brain MRI consideration depending on initial staging results. Treatment options discussed including surgical resection (lobectomy or pneumonectomy) for early stage disease. Alternative treatments include radiation therapy and chemotherapy if surgery not feasible. Targeted therapies and immunotherapy options available for selected cases. Potential side effects of treatments reviewed including surgical risks, radiation-related fatigue and skin changes, and chemotherapy-associated nausea, alopecia and infection risk.\n\nYours sincerely\n\nRespiratory Physician',
    'Respiratory Clinic Letter',
    259,
    '2025-11-22 18:32:59'
);
